  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IOM &#x2013; Multi Country Humanitarian Assistance &#x2013; CAP 2021</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">More than a decade of conflict, insecurity and armed attacks by the Non-State Armed Groups (NSAG) in north-east Nigeria, particularly in Borno, Adamawa and Yobe (BAY) States continue to be the main cause of the dire situation of the internally displaced persons (IDPs), returnees and other affected populations. They are the main drivers of vulnerabilities and protection concerns that the vulnerable populations face, including protracted displacement; human rights violations; gender-based violence; and sexual exploitation and abuse. IDPs in and outside camps have low coping mechanisms and are heavily reliant on humanitarian assistance. With the objective to contribute towards improving humanitarian service provision and strengthening coping mechanisms of the affected populations in north-east Nigeria, IOM, under this project, provides targeted interventions in the areas of Displacement Tracking Matrix (DTM) and mental health and psychosocial support.</narrative>
  </description>
